2 - COVID survey - interpret

This graph is showing the the answers for each of the 6 questions regarding vaccines (âVaccines are safeâ, âVaccines make me feel safer at workâ, âConcern over Vaccine Side Effectsâ, âVaccine vetting process confidenceâ, âvaccine information is trustworthyâ, and âI recommend the vaccineâ) for different identities from Age, Gender, Race, Ethnicity, Profession, or any prior vaccine experience for Covid and/or the flu. Starting from the top, for All data, most people tend to strongly agree on all questions regarding the vaccine except for âside effectsâ which is neutral. For age, there seems to be a trend where older people (>30) are more likely to believe in the vaccine and are closer to 1. Surprisingly, there was not a huge difference in gender across the 4 different options, with the exception of Non-binary, where the vaccine was more likely to be believed as less safe but also more likely to not be as concerned about the side effects as male or female respondents. As race goes, Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander and White respondents are more likely to have doubts about the vaccine. Both Hispanic and non-hispanic respondents were fairly equal. Surprisingly, nursing and medical professions had concerns over the side effects of the vaccine at a higher level than a good portion of the other population. Additionally, those who had had the vaccine were more wary of side effects, but those who havenât were much more generally doubtful, for both the COVID and Flu vaccine. Across the board, the question on vaccine safety and side effects garnered more varied responses than the others (much smaller error bars).

From my initial response, I agree with the graph in that those who havenât had vaccines this year are more likely to express higher levels of doubt around the covid vaccine for Flu and Covid. My intuition disagrees with the Nursing and Medical professions having significant doubts about the side effects, but more specifically how there are no other professions to compare to. I could be interpreting this response incorrect, and it may be something like âthe profession that gives you the vaccineâ, although I am unsure. Lastly, I also thought that younger people from <20 to 25 were more accepting of the vaccine and my intuition also disagrees with them having seemingly some of the greater concerns regarding the safety and side effects.

  • *Code after consulting with https://www.tidyverse.org/blog/2021/02/dplyr-1-0-4-if-any/. -1 from my own code, â~ !is.na(.)â formatting consulted from AI after multiple bug issues.
covid_survey <- covid |>
  
  #changes all the col values in accordance with directions
  mutate(
    "exp_already_vax" = if_else(exp_already_vax == 0, "No", "Yes"),
    
    "exp_flu_vax" = if_else(exp_flu_vax == 0, "No", "Yes"),
    
    "exp_profession" = if_else(exp_profession == 0, "Medical", "Nursing"),
    
    "exp_gender" = case_when(
      exp_gender == 0 ~ "Male",
      exp_gender == 1 ~ "Female",
      exp_gender == 3 ~ "Non-binary third gender",
      exp_gender == 4 ~ "Prefer not to say",
    ),
    
    "exp_race" = case_when(
      exp_race == 1 ~ "American Indian/Alaskan Native",
      exp_race == 2 ~ "Asian",
      exp_race == 3 ~ "Black/African American",
      exp_race == 4 ~ "Native Hawaiian/Other Pacific Islander",
      exp_race == 5 ~ "White"
    ),
    
    "exp_ethnicity" = if_else(exp_ethnicity == 1, "Hispanic/Latino", "Non-Hispanic/Non-Latino"),
    
    #age changed to factor so it can be easily ordered.
    "exp_age_bin" = factor(case_when(
      exp_age_bin == 0 ~ "<20",
      exp_age_bin == 20 ~ "21-25",
      exp_age_bin == 25 ~ "26-30",
      exp_age_bin == 30 ~ ">30"),
      
      levels = c("<20", "21-25", "26-30", ">30")), #*
    
    #response changed to double to appear close to reference dataframe
    "response_id" = as.double(response_id)
  )

  #creates a new column with all the response values. The row titles go in reponse, the values in response values.

  )

The graph with 25th and 75th quartile error bars reaffirms that safety of the vaccine and vaccine side effects have the greatest diversity of answers, while the other ones tend to be much closer to 1 or 2, meaning people approved of the vaccine more in those areas. The differences in Age also seem to be diminished with the smaller quartiles as well as the differences in Nursing and Medical. The differences between having taken or not taken the COVID vaccine are still quite distinct, which makes sense, but the differences in Flu vaccine got smaller.

*https://www.datacamp.com/tutorial/subsets-in-r **https://bookdown.org/rwnahhas/IntroToR/exclude-observations-with-missing-data.html

The Code chunk below and the diverging graph it generates was done following the guide made by https://rfortherestofus.com/2021/10/diverging-bar-chart

#Creates a dataframe that calculates the number of occurances per score and the percent of the question it makes up
resp_only_sum <- resp_only |>
  
  #groups by each question and each score
  group_by(question, score) %>%
  
  #counts the occurances and stores in n_answers
  count(name = "n_answers") |>
  
  #then group by questions to get the total sum of each question
  group_by(question) |>
  
  #creates a new column that gives the percent that each score makes up
  mutate(percent_answers = n_answers/sum(n_answers)) |>
  ungroup() |>
  
  #creates a new column where the percent gets transformed into a percent value
  mutate(percent_answers_label = percent(percent_answers, accuracy = 1),
         score_fill = as.character(score))

#creates a new dataframe for the diverging that classifies the lower values as postive and the higher values as negative, with 3 being 0
resp_diverging <- resp_only_sum |>
  #creates the column where 3 and lower are pos, 4 and higher are negative
  mutate(percent_answers_neg = if_else(score <=3, percent_answers, -percent_answers)) |>
  #creates the label so that it is not negative
  mutate(percent_answers_label = percent(percent_answers, accuracy = 1))

A. Image of a graph titled, âPercent response to COVID vaccine Questions that looks at the percent breakdown of scores (out of five, where one is strongly agree and 5 is strongly disagree) for six questions centered around the covid vaccine. The first question,âI will recommend the vaccine to family, friends, and community membersâ, has 88% of respondents strongly agreeing, while the other responses were relatively equal. The second question, âI trust the information that I have recieved about the vaccineâ, has 77% of respondents strongly agreeing and 21% agreeing. After that, the disagree and neutral categories were slightly more than the disagree respondents, although the three make up very little of the percentage. The third question is âI am confident in the scientific vetting process for the new COVID vaccinesâ which has a 61% strongly agree, 14% agree, and a 17% strongly disagree, with the other two responses both being at 4%. The fourth question, âI am concerned about the safety and side effects of the vaccineâ has 81% strongly agree, 10% agree, and minimal percent from the other responses. The fifth question, âGetting the vaccine will make me feel safer at workâ, has a 70% strongly agree, 23% agree, and minimal percentage for the other three. Lastly, the sixth question, âBased on my understanding, I believe the vaccine is safeâ, shows a significant deviation from the other questions, with 31% disagreeing, 24% agreeing, 22% strongly disagreeing, and only 12% strongly agreeing, leaving neutral responses at 11%. Ultimately, this graph highlights how most questions have respondents strongly agreeing, except for the question on vaccine safety, which is mixed, but tends slightly towards disagree.
